Maven doesn&#39;t inherently support skipping tests based on whether a module&#39;s source code has changed. However, you can approximate such functionality using a combination of Maven profiles and carefully crafted commands.

First, if you aren&#39;t using them already, modularize your code using Maven Modules. Each module should have its own pom.xml. Then, you can use Maven profiles to skip tests for each module:

    &lt;profile&gt;
        &lt;id&gt;skipTests&lt;/id&gt;
        &lt;properties&gt;
            &lt;maven.test.skip&gt;true&lt;/maven.test.skip&gt;
        &lt;/properties&gt;
    &lt;/profile&gt;
   &lt;/profiles&gt;

You can activate this profile when building a module to skip tests:

    mvn clean install -PskipTests

 - Checks which files have changed since the last commit.
 - Determines which module(s) those files belong to.
 - Builds only those modules without skipping tests.
 - Builds the rest of the modules with the skipTests profile active.

